<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[155,794,164,1956]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The few specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[428,589,1145,1167]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[428,589,1145,1167]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Solanum aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have usually been annotated as the more common and widely distributed 
<taxonomicName authority="Dunal" authorityName="Dunal" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aureum">
<emphasis box="[707,793,1173,1195]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aureum</emphasis>
Dunal
</taxonomicName>
, also from Andean Ecuador. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[514,669,1202,1224]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[514,669,1202,1224]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Solanum aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from that species in its simple uniseriate, rather than congesteddendritic pubescence (
<figureCitation box="[370,436,1258,1280]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[155,220,1887,1906]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,961,1847]" captionTargetId="figure-451@1.[155,1006,954,1854]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Solanum aspersum. A) portion of stem, with details of trichomes, B) young bud, C) open flower, D) fruiting inflorescence, E) young fruit. A–C drawn from MacDougal et al. 4251, D–E from Zak 1857A. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517440" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517440/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig 1A</figureCitation>
), and in the elongate buds that open to deeply stellate flowers (
<figureCitation box="[403,503,1286,1308]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[155,220,1887,1906]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,961,1847]" captionTargetId="figure-451@1.[155,1006,954,1854]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Solanum aspersum. A) portion of stem, with details of trichomes, B) young bud, C) open flower, D) fruiting inflorescence, E) young fruit. A–C drawn from MacDougal et al. 4251, D–E from Zak 1857A. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517440" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517440/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1B, C</figureCitation>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dunal" box="[656,740,1286,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aureum">
<emphasis box="[656,740,1286,1308]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Azuay province in Ecuador have similarly shiny adaxial leaf surfaces to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[268,368,1342,1364]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[268,368,1342,1364]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but always have the characteristic golden dendritic pubescence of that species rather than the simple pubescence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[305,407,1398,1420]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[305,407,1398,1420]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The leaves of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[572,673,1398,1420]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[572,673,1398,1420]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually more cordate than those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dunal" box="[431,516,1426,1447]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aureum">
<emphasis box="[431,516,1426,1447]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but some populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dunal" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aureum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
approach 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[329,432,1454,1475]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[329,432,1454,1475]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">S. aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in overall leaf morphology at first glance. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[230,383,1482,1503]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aspersum">
<emphasis box="[230,383,1482,1503]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Solanum aspersum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very scattered distribution all along the Andes from northern Colombia to central Ecuador and is likely to be found in more of the intervening parts of the cordilleras, but it is apparently rare and easily overlooked.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
